  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much does an Olympic gold medal cost?",
  "response": "The monetary value of an Olympic gold medal is not straightforward, as it combines the intrinsic value of the materials used and the symbolic value associated with the achievement. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. **Material Cost:**\n   - Olympic gold medals are not made of solid gold. Since 1912, they have been primarily composed of silver with a thin plating of gold. \n   - The gold plating is usually about 6 grams of pure gold.\n   - As of the last update, the price of gold hovered around $60,000 per kilogram. Therefore, 6 grams of gold would be worth approximately $360.\n   - The rest of the medal is silver, which weighs around 550 grams for a total medal weight of about 556 grams. With silver prices around $700 per kilogram, the silver component would be worth approximately $385.\n   - So, the total material value of an Olympic gold medal would be roughly $745.\n\n2. **Symbolic and Market Value:**\n   - The symbolic value of an Olympic gold medal is immense, representing years of hard work, dedication, and achievement at the highest level of sport.\n   - Due to this prestige, gold medalists have occasionally auctioned their medals, and they can fetch significantly higher prices. For instance, medals have been sold at auctions for anywhere between $10,000 to over $1 million, depending on the sport, the athlete, and the historical significance of the win.\n\nIn summary, while the material cost of an Olympic gold medal is around $745, its market value at auction can be substantially higher, often reflecting the fame of the athlete and the significance of the Olympic event.",
